---
import CalculatorLayout from '@layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import { ProjectRateCalc } from '@components/calculators/ProjectRateCalc';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How do I convert my hourly rate to a project rate?',
    answer:
      'Start by estimating the total hours needed, then multiply by your hourly rate. Add buffer for scope creep (15-20%), revision time, and a profit margin. This calculator automates this process and suggests tiered pricing options.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I charge hourly or project-based?',
    answer:
      'Project-based pricing is often better for both parties. Clients get cost certainty, and you can earn more if you work efficiently. However, hourly works better for ongoing or undefined scope work. Many freelancers use project rates for defined deliverables.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much scope buffer should I include?',
    answer:
      'A 10-20% scope buffer is standard for well-defined projects. For vague or complex projects, consider 25-30%. This protects you from scope creep and unexpected complications. It\'s better to come in under budget than to ask for more money.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I handle rush fees?',
    answer:
      'Rush fees compensate for the disruption to your schedule and the stress of tight deadlines. Standard rush fees are 25-50% extra for accelerated timelines, and 75-100% for emergency/same-day work. Always communicate these upfront.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What if the project takes longer than estimated?',
    answer:
      'This is why scope buffers and clear contracts matter. Define exactly what\'s included in the project price. Additional work beyond scope should be billed separately. Track your time to improve future estimates.',
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  {
    name: 'Freelancer Hourly Rate Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate your ideal hourly rate based on income goals',
    href: '/freelance/hourly-rate-calculator',
    category: 'Freelance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Quarterly Tax Estimator',
    description: 'Estimate your quarterly tax payments',
    href: '/freelance/quarterly-tax-calculator',
    category: 'Freelance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Substack Revenue Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate newsletter subscription earnings',
    href: '/creator/substack-calculator',
    category: 'Creator',
  },
  {
    name: 'Meeting Cost Calculator',
    description: 'See the true cost of meetings including hidden overhead',
    href: '/freelance/meeting-cost-calculator',
    category: 'Freelance',
  },
];
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title="Project Rate Calculator - Convert Hourly to Project Pricing"
  description="Calculate project-based pricing from your hourly rate. Includes scope buffer, revision rounds, complexity adjustments, and tiered pricing suggestions."
  calculatorName="Project Rate Calculator"
  category="Freelance"
  categorySlug="freelance"
  slug="project-rate-calculator"
  ogImage="/og-images/project-rate.png"
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
>
  <ProjectRateCalc client:visible />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>How to Use the Project Rate Calculator</h2>
        <p>Project-based pricing gives clients cost certainty and lets you earn more as you get faster. This calculator converts your hourly rate into a well-structured project quote with built-in protections for scope changes and revisions.</p>
        <h3>Quick Mode</h3>
        <p>Enter your hourly rate and the estimated number of hours the project will take. The calculator applies a default scope buffer and produces a recommended project price. This is perfect for replying to quick inquiries or ballparking quotes in a discovery call.</p>
        <h3>Advanced Mode</h3>
        <p>Switch to Advanced when you need a detailed proposal. You can adjust the scope buffer percentage, set a complexity multiplier for technically demanding work, define the number of revision rounds included, and generate tiered pricing options (basic, standard, and premium packages). Tiered pricing is a proven strategy for increasing average deal size by letting clients self-select the level of service they need.</p>
        <h3>Setting the Right Scope Buffer</h3>
        <p>The scope buffer is your safety net against underestimating. For well-defined projects with clear deliverables, 10 to 15 percent is usually sufficient. For projects with vague requirements or multiple stakeholders, bump it to 20 to 30 percent. If you find yourself consistently using the full buffer, your initial hour estimates may need recalibration.</p>
        <h3>Practical Tips</h3>
        <p>Track your time on every project, even when billing a flat rate. This data improves future estimates and helps you identify which project types are most profitable. Always define in your contract exactly what is included in the quoted price and what constitutes additional work billed separately. Clear scope boundaries protect both you and your client from misunderstandings down the road.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
